# Component & Screen Patterns

## Component Declaration

Always use **named function declarations** (not arrow functions assigned to `const`):

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
export function MyComponent(props: MyComponentProps) { ... }

// ❌ BAD
export const MyComponent = (props: MyComponentProps) => { ... }
```

## Export Pattern

Every component file must have **both** a named export on the function **and** a default export at the bottom. The barrel `index.ts` always re-exports via `export { default as X }`:

```tsx
// ✅ ComponentName.tsx
export function MyComponent(props: MyComponentProps) { ... }

export default MyComponent;
```

Barrel `index.ts` must split components and types into two clearly separated sections:

```ts
// ✅ index.ts
// ─── Components ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export { default as MyComponent } from './MyComponent';
export { default as AnotherComponent } from './AnotherComponent';

// ─── Props ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export type { MyComponentProps } from './MyComponent';
export type { AnotherComponentProps } from './AnotherComponent';

// ❌ BAD — interleaved components and types
export { default as MyComponent } from './MyComponent';
export type { MyComponentProps } from './MyComponent';

// ❌ BAD — named-only export
export { MyComponent } from './MyComponent';
```

---

## Props Typing

Define props as a local `interface` or `type` above the component:

```tsx
interface MyComponentProps {
  value: string;
  onChange: (value: string) => void;
}

export function MyComponent({ value, onChange }: MyComponentProps) { ... }
```

Use **discriminated unions** for polymorphic components (see `FormInput.tsx`):

```tsx
type FormInputProps<TFieldValues extends FieldValues, TName extends Path<TFieldValues>> =
  | { type: 'text'; inputProps: TextInputProps<TFieldValues, TName> }
  | { type: 'select'; selectProps: SelectProps<TFieldValues, TName> }
  | { type: 'radio'; radioProps: RadioProps<TFieldValues, TName> };
```

## Generic Components

Use generic type parameters for reusable components:

```tsx
export function FormInput<
  TFieldValues extends FieldValues,
  TName extends Path<TFieldValues>,
>(props: FormInputProps<TFieldValues, TName>) { ... }
```

## Containers vs Components

| Location | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| `src/containers/` | Screen-level logic — Redux dispatch, form state, navigation calls |
| `src/components/` | Pure presentational — no Redux, no navigation, only props |

## Forms (react-hook-form + yup)

```tsx
const schema = yup.object({ email: yup.string().email().required() });

const { control, handleSubmit } = useForm<FormValues>({
  resolver: yupResolver(schema),
});

// Use FormInput with control prop — never raw TextInput for form fields
<FormInput control={control} name="email" type="text" ... />
```

## Common Components

Always use components from `~components/common` instead of the raw React Native equivalents.

### Text

Use `Text` from `~components/common` — never import `Text` directly from `react-native`:

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
import { Text } from '~components/common';

<Text style={tw`text-sm text-gray-900`}>Hello</Text>

// ❌ BAD
import { Text } from 'react-native';
```

The custom `Text` applies the project's base font styles via `twrnc` and ensures consistent typography across the app. Any global text defaults (font family, scaling, etc.) only need to be changed in one place.

### Modal

Use `Modal` from `~components/common` instead of `react-native`'s `Modal`:

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
import { Modal } from '~components/common';

// ❌ BAD
import { Modal } from 'react-native';
```

---

## i18n

Always use `useTranslation` — never hardcode user-facing strings:

```tsx
const { t } = useTranslation();
<Text>{t('common.submit')}</Text>
```
